      "question": "If the prime factorization of a positive integer $N$ is given by $N = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^k$ and it is known that $N$ is divisible by $1000$, then the smallest possible integer value of $k$ is:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the prime factorization of $1000$ as $10^3 = (2 \times 5)^3 = 2^3 \times 5^3$.",
          "For $N$ to be divisible by $1000$, all prime factors of $1000$ must be present in the prime factorization of $N$ with exponents greater than or equal to those in $1000$.",
          "Given $N = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^k$. Comparing the powers of $5$, we must have $k \\geq 3$.",
          "The smallest integer $k$ satisfying this condition is $3$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$1000 = 10^3 = (2 \\times 5)^3 = 2^3 \\times 5^3 \\\\ N = 2^3 \\times 3^2 \\times 5^k \\\\ \\text{For } 1000 \\mid N, \\text{ the power of } 5 \\text{ in } N \\text{ must be } \\geq \\text{ the power of } 5 \\text{ in } 1000 \\\\ k \\geq 3 \\\\ k_{min} = 3$"
      },
